WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:05.760
The Great Pyramids of Giza, rank among the&nbsp;
oldest monuments of Egyptian architecture,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:05.760 --> 00:00:09.520
and they’re even among the oldest&nbsp;
buildings still preserved today.

00:00:09.520 --> 00:00:14.080
They were built within the necropolis&nbsp;
of the ancient capital city of Memphis,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:18.960
where the fourth dynasty pharaohs&nbsp;
ruled about 4500 years ago.

00:00:18.960 --> 00:00:23.600
When you go and see the pyramids,&nbsp;
overwhelms you the amount of material,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:32.000
and the massiveness of each stone, the amount of&nbsp;
labor that these constructions must have required.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.480
If you traveled back to 2500 BC,&nbsp;
the time the pyramids were built,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:40.320
you would see these huge white masses&nbsp;
shining in the middle of the desert,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:44.400
for they had a very different&nbsp;
finish from the one we see today.

00:00:45.120 --> 00:00:48.880
Pharaohs built the pyramids in their&nbsp;
lifetime as their future tombs to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:53.280
secure immortality by the preservation&nbsp;
of their mummy, until the time when,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:58.720
according to their belief, the soul&nbsp;
would once more return to the body.

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:04.880
Egyptian pyramids are square in plan, and their&nbsp;
faces are generally equilateral triangles.

00:01:04.880 --> 00:01:08.320
The sides face directly north, south, east,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:12.800
and west, aligning with the&nbsp;
cycle of Ra, god of the sun.

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:16.720
Most pyramids have their&nbsp;
entrance on their northern side,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:22.240
which gives access to a passage sloping&nbsp;
downwards to a chamber below the ground.

00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:28.640
However, each pyramid varies slightly&nbsp;
on its design and internal distribution.

00:01:28.640 --> 00:01:33.120
The Great Pyramids of Giza are three—Cheops,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:40.400
Chephren, and Mycerinos—each named after the&nbsp;
Pharaoh who commissioned its construction.

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:47.600
The Pyramid of Cheops, the oldest of the three,&nbsp;
is the largest mass of stone ever erected by man.

00:01:47.600 --> 00:01:55.920
It was originally 146 meters high, with&nbsp;
each of its faces measuring 230 meters long.

00:01:55.920 --> 00:02:01.600
Its faces make an angle of&nbsp;
51 degrees with the ground.

00:02:01.600 --> 00:02:05.200
Today it is somewhat smaller&nbsp;
than its original dimensions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:08.880
as the white outer casing has disappeared.

00:02:10.320 --> 00:02:14.640
This pyramid has three internal&nbsp;
chambers: the subterranean chamber,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:14.640 --> 00:02:18.880
the Queen’s Chamber, and the King’s Chamber.

00:02:18.880 --> 00:02:24.640
Due to changes of plan during the construction,&nbsp;
the subterranean chamber was a discarded project,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:29.760
abandoned in favor of placing the burial&nbsp;
chamber higher up inside the pyramid.

00:02:29.760 --> 00:02:35.120
As a result, this underground chamber&nbsp;
appears irregular and even unfinished;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:42.880
its rough walls reflect the fact that it was cut&nbsp;
directly into the bedrock beneath the pyramid.

00:02:42.880 --> 00:02:46.320
The Queen’s Chamber, whose&nbsp;
name was given in modern times,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:55.200
probably contained a large statue of Cheops,&nbsp;
serving as his spirit chamber, called serdab.

00:02:55.200 --> 00:02:59.520
The King’s Chamber was built to contain&nbsp;
the granite sarcophagus of the Pharaoh,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:02.560
which you can still see inside.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.000
You can notice the change in material&nbsp;
that was used for this chamber,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:11.040
indicating the importance of this room.

00:03:11.040 --> 00:03:15.680
It’s all made of red granite, same as&nbsp;
the great beams set above the chamber.

00:03:15.680 --> 00:03:17.920
Granite is a much harder stone,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:22.560
so it helped to transfer the tremendous&nbsp;
weight of the pyramid around the chamber.

00:03:23.200 --> 00:03:27.440
If you look closely, you’ll find two&nbsp;
small openings inside the chamber,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:27.440 --> 00:03:32.880
which are thought to be ventilation shafts&nbsp;
that lead to the exterior of the building,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:37.520
although their precise function and&nbsp;
symbolic meaning remain unclear.

00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:43.840
The passage leading to this chamber, known as the&nbsp;
Grand Gallery, is itself a marvel of construction.

00:03:43.840 --> 00:03:47.520
A corbeled vault rises eight&nbsp;
and a half meters vertically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:47.520 --> 00:03:51.760
creating an impressive corridor that&nbsp;
contrasts with the one-meter-high&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:51.760 --> 00:03:55.680
corridor you have to go through&nbsp;
before reaching the Grand Gallery.

00:03:55.680 --> 00:03:59.120
It can be challenging to go through this corridor,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:59.120 --> 00:04:09.680
but upon reaching the Grand Gallery, you&nbsp;
feel the cool air flowing inside the pyramid.

00:04:09.680 --> 00:04:14.080
When entering the Great Pyramid, you access&nbsp;
not through the original entrance made by the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.080 --> 00:04:20.880
Egyptians, but through a tunnel that was excavated&nbsp;
in the Middle Ages by a caliph called Al-Ma’mun.

00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:25.280
His men didn’t know where the original&nbsp;
entrance was located because it was sealed,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:25.280 --> 00:04:30.000
and much of the pyramid’s surface was still&nbsp;
covered with the original white casing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.880
but they knew where to look—they knew pyramids&nbsp;
have their entrances on the north side, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:41.440
they opened the tunnel in the center, at a height&nbsp;
they assumed would intersect the internal system.

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:46.720
The tunnel was carved using simple tools&nbsp;
available during the medieval period,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:50.000
which is why you can distinguish the rough, hasty,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:56.080
and uneven tunnel from the neat, smooth&nbsp;
original passageways of the pyramid.

00:04:56.080 --> 00:05:02.960
By chance, their tunnel intersected the Descending&nbsp;
Passage, which leads to the internal chambers.

00:05:02.960 --> 00:05:09.680
When they entered, they found the&nbsp;
chambers empty, no treasure and no mummy.

00:05:09.680 --> 00:05:15.200
Since the main entrance was still sealed, it is&nbsp;
likely that the pyramid was robbed in antiquity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:20.400
shortly after the pyramid was finished,&nbsp;
as people still knew the internal layout,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:25.120
the location of the hidden mechanisms,&nbsp;
and how sealing systems worked,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:26.400 --> 00:05:34.320
so the robbers were most&nbsp;
probably ancient Egyptians.

00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:37.760
The second-largest pyramid is that of Chephren,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:42.960
easily recognizable by its upper section,&nbsp;
which still preserves its original casing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:42.960 --> 00:05:48.480
giving you an idea of the powerful&nbsp;
appearance that these pyramids once had.

00:05:49.520 --> 00:05:53.600
The Pyramid of Chephren rose&nbsp;
to a height of 143 meters,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:53.600 --> 00:05:57.600
and each side measures 215 meters at the base.

00:05:57.600 --> 00:06:01.840
Though smaller in its base, the height&nbsp;
is very close to that of Cheops’ pyramid,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.840 --> 00:06:05.920
because of its steeper slope of 53 degrees.

00:06:05.920 --> 00:06:12.000
If you visit the site you might get the impression&nbsp;
that this is the tallest of the three pyramids,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:18.160
but that’s because it’s built on a&nbsp;
higher ground than that of Cheops.

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:23.840
For some reason, this pyramid has two northern&nbsp;
entrances, one leading through a subterranean&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:30.720
passageway, and the other through the stonework,&nbsp;
both leading to a single underground tomb chamber.

00:06:30.720 --> 00:06:34.960
This pyramid was first opened in&nbsp;
1818 by Italian explorer Giovanni&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:34.960 --> 00:06:38.640
Battista Belzoni, who found the original entrance.

00:06:38.640 --> 00:06:44.400
In the 19th century, the pyramids were much&nbsp;
more stripped from their original casing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:44.400 --> 00:06:48.960
and Belzoni, who knew the entrance&nbsp;
was somewhere in the northern face,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:48.960 --> 00:06:54.800
noticed a horizontal gap in the masonry of the&nbsp;
base, with a slightly different stone dressing.

00:06:54.800 --> 00:06:57.600
This anomaly marked the entrance corridor.

00:06:57.600 --> 00:07:00.560
Belzoni excavated directly into the blockage,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:00.560 --> 00:07:05.200
instead of excavating blindly like the&nbsp;
medieval caliph in the other pyramid.

00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:08.240
He entered and found the chamber empty,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.240 --> 00:07:14.800
so this pyramid was likely also robbed very&nbsp;
early, during the Old Kingdom of Egypt.

00:07:14.800 --> 00:07:22.400
Belzoni inscribed in the wall “Scoperta da&nbsp;
G. Belzoni 2 mar. 1818” which is Italian&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:22.400 --> 00:07:28.160
for “discovered by G. Belzoni march 2nd 1818”.

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:31.920
Belzoni found an empty granite&nbsp;
sarcophagus at the end of the chamber,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.920 --> 00:07:36.640
which has a gabled roof made&nbsp;
with massive limestone beams.

00:07:37.840 --> 00:07:42.880
The Pyramid of Mycerinos is considerably&nbsp;
smaller than the other two, and it also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:54.960
conserves part of its original casing, which,&nbsp;
as you can see, is different from the other two:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:54.960 --> 00:07:59.920
this one had a granite casing on the&nbsp;
bottom half, and limestone on the top.

00:08:00.640 --> 00:08:04.000
Like the other two, this pyramid was&nbsp;
robbed in antiquity, and the first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:10.320
documented entry by European explorers&nbsp;
in the 1830s, found the chambers empty.

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:14.800
As in the others, the entrance is on the north&nbsp;
side, and here you enter through the granite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:14.800 --> 00:08:21.840
casing, and walk down through a narrow&nbsp;
corridor that’s about thirty meters long.

00:08:21.840 --> 00:08:25.920
The pyramids weren’t made for modern&nbsp;
tourists to go up and down all the time,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:28.240
so it is difficult to navigate.

00:08:28.240 --> 00:08:30.880
At the end of the initial descending passage,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:30.880 --> 00:08:35.840
you reach a first small chamber that has a&nbsp;
few relief pattern carvings on the walls.

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:39.760
These imitate the vernacular&nbsp;
architecture of an Egyptian house,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:44.000
as this is probably a room where the&nbsp;
statue of the Pharaoh was located.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:47.520
As in Cheops’ pyramid, this one&nbsp;
has a system of granite blocks&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:51.760
that would fall on this room to seal the entrance.

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:55.760
After the second small corridor&nbsp;
you reach a larger chamber with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:55.760 --> 00:09:02.640
an access to the underground main chamber.

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:06.000
You descend another small&nbsp;
passage and enter the chamber,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:10.480
which has a granite curved&nbsp;
vault covered in graffiti.

00:09:10.480 --> 00:09:15.040
Graffiti inside pyramids was&nbsp;
very common in the 19th century.

00:09:15.040 --> 00:09:20.000
Early explorers and travelers&nbsp;
often left their initials on walls.

00:09:21.920 --> 00:09:26.960
Mycerinos’ sarcophagus is said to have been&nbsp;
beautifully crafted from black basalt with rich&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:34.560
detail, but unfortunately was taken by the British&nbsp;
and lost in a shipwreck on its way to Britain.

00:09:34.560 --> 00:09:36.800
The pyramids were laid out on the bedrock,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:36.800 --> 00:09:41.280
which is a solid layer of limestone that&nbsp;
lies underneath the sand of the desert.

00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:44.480
This bedrock was leveled to&nbsp;
provide a stable foundation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:44.480 --> 00:09:49.600
to receive the weight of the massive structures.

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:54.080
For the most part, local limestone was&nbsp;
used for the construction of the pyramids,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:54.080 --> 00:09:57.840
except for the casing, for which&nbsp;
a finer limestone was brought from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:57.840 --> 00:10:03.600
the opposite side of the river, and&nbsp;
for the granite, used primarily for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:03.600 --> 00:10:08.560
the linings of some of the chambers and&nbsp;
passages as it is a much harder stone.

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:15.840
The granite was transported down the&nbsp;
Nile from Aswan, in the south of Egypt.

00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:20.400
So each pyramid had a limestone core,&nbsp;
faced with a finer limestone that was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:26.320
polished for a smooth white finish&nbsp;
that reflected the rays of the sun.

00:10:26.320 --> 00:10:30.640
The apex stone, called Pyramidion,&nbsp;
was probably gilded with an alloy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:30.640 --> 00:10:35.760
of gold and silver, although there is&nbsp;
not enough evidence to confirm this.

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:40.880
These capstones were made of finer materials,&nbsp;
because the pyramids were associated with Ra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:40.880 --> 00:10:48.080
the sun, and they were meant to reflect&nbsp;
the sunlight, connecting Earth and Heaven.

00:10:48.080 --> 00:10:53.720
The pyramids were not isolated structures, but&nbsp;
rather, they were the main part of a funerary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:53.720 --> 00:10:59.200
complex, composed by the tomb proper, which is&nbsp;
the pyramid itself, a mortuary temple, located on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:59.200 --> 00:11:04.960
the east of the pyramid at its foot, which served&nbsp;
for veneration and offerings to the dead, a long&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:04.960 --> 00:11:11.520
causeway, and a Valley Temple, where the corpse&nbsp;
was received for purification and mummification.

00:11:11.520 --> 00:11:15.360
A canal was built connecting the&nbsp;
river Nile with the Valley Temple,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:15.360 --> 00:11:18.560
by which the funeral procession arrived.

00:11:18.560 --> 00:11:21.280
Egyptian architecture is all about the procession.

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:25.920
Procession is the protagonist in Egyptian&nbsp;
architecture, and you can clearly see this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:25.920 --> 00:11:31.680
notion of movement governed by the axes in&nbsp;
the way the pyramid complex is laid out.

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:35.520
The causeways are not parallel, and the causeway&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:41.680
repeats the direction of the pyramid&nbsp;
itself only on the Mycerinos complex.

00:11:41.680 --> 00:11:46.800
Surrounding the pyramids, a&nbsp;
city of mastabas is disposed.

00:11:46.800 --> 00:11:51.680
A mastaba was a type of Egyptian&nbsp;
tomb structure characterized by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:51.680 --> 00:11:56.640
its rectangular shape with a&nbsp;
flat roof and sloping sides.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.040
Mastabas typically have a shaft and an underground&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:01.040 --> 00:12:08.160
chamber for burial, and a small room&nbsp;
for offerings on the ground level.

00:12:08.160 --> 00:12:16.960
They are often decorated with inscriptions and&nbsp;
reliefs inside, and a false door carved in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:16.960 --> 00:12:22.320
wall that represents the passageway&nbsp;
into the afterlife for the deceased.

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:28.400
The smaller pyramids were built for&nbsp;
the burial of royal family members,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:28.400 --> 00:12:33.600
and the mastabas were for nobles,&nbsp;
priests, and court officials.

00:12:33.600 --> 00:12:37.920
They were buried near the pharaoh because&nbsp;
they believed that proximity to him would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:37.920 --> 00:12:42.640
ensure a more favorable journey to the afterlife.

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:44.880
Situated in front of the great pyramids,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:44.880 --> 00:12:50.240
at the entrance of the complex,&nbsp;
is the great Sphinx of Giza.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.080
Its site used to be a stone quarry,&nbsp;
from where much of the limestone used&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:56.080 --> 00:13:00.080
for the pyramids’ construction&nbsp;
was extracted, and it was carved&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:12.480
from a natural spur of rock to resemble a&nbsp;
Sphinx with rough masonry added in parts.

00:13:12.480 --> 00:13:18.080
An Egyptian Sphinx had the head of a&nbsp;
king or a ram on the body of a lion.

00:13:18.640 --> 00:13:27.680
They were often placed at the entrance of temples,&nbsp;
and their role was to protect sacred places.

00:13:27.680 --> 00:13:33.760
This Sphinx of Giza bears the face of Chephren,&nbsp;
the Pharaoh who built the second pyramid, wearing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:33.760 --> 00:13:43.600
the royal head-dress, the false beard, and cobra&nbsp;
brow ornament—symbols of divinity and kingship.

00:13:44.240 --> 00:13:47.120
Between the paws, there is a large granite stele&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:47.120 --> 00:13:54.800
that records a restoration made to the&nbsp;
Sphinx by Thutmose IV in the 1400s BC.

00:13:54.800 --> 00:14:02.080
The Sphinx is about seventy meters long,&nbsp;
and twenty meters high in its highest point.

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:07.760
Its face is four meters wide, and&nbsp;
its mouth is over two meters long.

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:11.280
Although greatly mutilated,&nbsp;
especially in the nose,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:11.280 --> 00:14:15.840
it is still a marvel, as it&nbsp;
has been throughout the ages.

00:14:15.840 --> 00:14:19.520
It is thought that it was carved&nbsp;
to guard the complex of Chephren,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:19.520 --> 00:14:25.680
but much about its construction and date is&nbsp;
still a mystery, and probably ever will be.

00:14:25.680 --> 00:14:30.000
If you compare other Ancient Egyptian&nbsp;
funerary complexes, you may notice that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:35.120
there is a lack of articulation and&nbsp;
decoration in the whole Giza complex.

00:14:35.120 --> 00:14:42.640
Take a look at Saqqara for example, possibly&nbsp;
the oldest pyramid complex in Egypt.

00:14:42.640 --> 00:14:50.400
Here you have columns articulating surfaces, most&nbsp;
of them decorated with papyrus and lotus capitals,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:55.680
some of them have fluting imitating&nbsp;
a bundle of reeds from the river,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:55.680 --> 00:15:02.880
and you have reliefs, and hieroglyphic&nbsp;
inscriptions on the walls of buildings.

00:15:05.920 --> 00:15:12.880
These articulating details and decoration have&nbsp;
been abolished in the Giza complex—you see square,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:18.480
monolithic pillars and lintels in the Valley&nbsp;
Temples, there is no relief decoration nor&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:18.480 --> 00:15:24.080
hieroglyphic inscriptions even inside the&nbsp;
pyramids, not even the sarcophagus has a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:24.080 --> 00:15:32.080
single inscription, all to strengthen the effect&nbsp;
of the smooth surfaces and pure geometric shapes.

00:15:32.080 --> 00:15:37.920
The spaces appear as if they were&nbsp;
excavated within large masses of stone.

00:15:37.920 --> 00:15:44.080
The Giza complex represents extreme&nbsp;
simplicity and abstraction—no ornament,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:44.080 --> 00:15:50.480
smooth surface, and pure geometric&nbsp;
shapes, and clear orthogonal space,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:50.480 --> 00:15:57.520
strengthening the mass, clarity of form,&nbsp;
and the feeling of permanence and eternity.

00:15:58.160 --> 00:16:04.080
Even though interior spaces exist, they&nbsp;
feel like they are cut out from solid stone.

00:16:04.080 --> 00:16:09.360
The building feels more like a single&nbsp;
mass rather than a collection of rooms.

00:16:09.360 --> 00:16:12.640
The pyramid is the expression of massive building,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:12.640 --> 00:16:17.360
it’s the peak of Egyptian concern&nbsp;
with durability and eternity.

00:16:17.360 --> 00:16:23.120
The impression given to the mind of the spectator,&nbsp;
is that these buildings were erected for eternity.

00:16:23.120 --> 00:16:26.400
The remains have a character of immense solidity.

00:16:26.400 --> 00:16:41.360
The pyramids are the most extravagant&nbsp;
of all ancient buildings in many ways.

00:16:55.680 --> 00:16:56.480
Thanks for watching.

00:16:56.480 --> 00:16:57.920
I hope you enjoyed and learned.

00:16:57.920 --> 00:17:01.760
Please like this video, subscribe to my&nbsp;
channel, and if you like these videos,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:01.760 --> 00:17:06.160
you can watch longer versions of them&nbsp;
if you join as a channel member, there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:06.160 --> 00:17:09.920
I explain a lot more details, more&nbsp;
about the construction of the pyramids,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:09.920 --> 00:17:13.760
and more mysterious things about&nbsp;
the Giza complex and other places.

00:17:13.760 --> 00:17:16.800
Thank you for watching and I'll see&nbsp;
you very soon in another episode.

00:17:16.800 --> 00:17:17.440
Goodbye!

